         <abstract>
            <p>Given an odd prime p we show a way to construct large families of polynomials P&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt;(x) ∈  Q[x], q ∈ C, where C is a set of primes of the form q &lt;tex-math&gt;$\equiv$&lt;/tex-math&gt; 1 mod p and P&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt;(x) is the irreducible polynomial of the Gaussian periods of degree p in  Q(ζ&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt;). Examples of these families when p = 7 are worked in detail. We also show, given an integer n ≥ 2 and a prime 1 &lt;tex-math&gt;$\equiv$&lt;/tex-math&gt; 1 mod 2n, how to represent by matrices the Gaussian periods η&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;,...,η&lt;sub&gt;n-1&lt;/sub&gt; of degree n in  Q(ζ&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt;), and how to calculate in a simple way, with the help of a computer, irreducible polynomials for elements of  Q(η&lt;sub&gt;0&lt;/sub&gt;).</p>
          </abstract>
